## About this Noiselog

Small technical updates, reviews, and insights into the things we are working
on. Written by Chris.

You can [subscribe to this page via
RSS]($link.page('noiselog').alternative('rss')).

This page lists entries for the year 2025, for past or future entries consult
the [noiselog archive](/noiselog/).

## [Pick a colour]($section.id("2025-11-25T10:09:43"))

Any new artist needs a recognisable art style, and it certainly helps to stay
consistent across photos, logos, videos, fonts -- even the way you write. These
things can evolve, of course. Traditionally (since the 60s), bands have tied
changes in their visual identity to album cycles. I’m not convinced the
_“album”_ should be the milestone musicians organise themselves around
anymore, but that’s a conversation for another day.

Once you’ve settled on a colour you like, building a palette around it has
never been easier. You don’t need a degree in colour theory to open up
[coolors.co][coolors] or [color-hex.com][color-hex] and happily experiment
until something fits your aesthetic.

It didn’t take us long to land on the red we wanted. A mix of French New Wave
posters, Tarantino’s stylised grit, and some striking Queen’s Gambit fan art
nudged us towards the rather seductive
**[#c60420]($text.attrs("polgar-red"))**.

-- Chris

[coolors]: https://coolors.co/
[color-hex]: https://www.color-hex.com/

## [Hello, World!]($section.id("2025-11-24T16:19:00"))

What the hell is a noiselog?

It's like a devlog. So what's a devlog?  > _"A devlog is a blog or diary that
updates an audience on the > development progress of a project, typically a
video game, website, or app."_ > > [Wiktionary][devlog]

**Why do this?** I like microblogging, nerding out about music, coding, audio
tech, and how musicians work behind the scenes. The more in-depth stuff will
probably end up in the [blog]($link.page("blog")). Also, with this outlet, I
can avoid nerding out on social media... too much.

-- Chris

[devlog]: https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/devlog
